my name is Luis and yes, I'm addicted to technology since I was a kid, I had the privilege and the curse to be diagnosed with ADHD since an early age, causing not only hyperfocusing fascination around computers while battling basic management descitions and borderline autism behaviours, yet staying functional enough as a human being.

 let's start with my first computer, ... yeah this badboy I managed to restore it to a functional point to it's old glory, one of my uncle bringer up this baggage brick from Europe, It barely ran a text editor and basic MS-DOS stuff but I have faint memories of sitting in someone's lap while admiring the primitive pre 90's console work.

could it be I was destined to become one of those long beard wizards that compiled operative systems in C?.... I doubt I'll ever be as great as those super heroes from the 80's but for your entertaining purposes I'm still fathoming the idea, today everything is possible with AI. even decompiling old legacy forgotten software, friction is gone we are now free to dive deep so let's do it.  ... 

aside from being a complete pain in the ass and problematic child that had to change multiple times (5) from different schools for not being able to concentrate properly up to the point to be hooked up with Ritalin to ease me up, I always had a computer at reach.

be it damaged, functional or even personal I always had the tools at my disposal to try and test different systems, mostly windows at first I sadly admit. Linux was completely underground for myself while trying games on MSDos like price of Persia,3D Tetris or sokoban, I thank my brother for sourcing them up in diskette form, that was my entry level until windows 95 and 98 came up to open my world curiosity and widen up my knowledge with Encarta 97 and multiple amazing games. I still question myself how I was able to get my hands on so many games early on, tomb raider,diablo,lost Eden, time commander, there wasn't a shortage on CDs more like an endless Multimedia supplies of 90's educational kids software. ...


fast forward to my 2000's middle school it was clear I was good with them, not only I could tear them apart and fix them but I also blame those games to give me the English language advantage early on, if I needed to sell trade or pretty much understand any interaction in games I needed English. there wasn't a Spanish translation, just a huge black hardcover book English dictionary nearby a Carmen San Diego flag encyclopedia to catch on what was going on, I could write proficiently on a keyboard I could understood how to unfreeze unstuck unreliable hardware failures from windows XP and how to stay at SP1 even sp2 before even daring to try vista (it was terrible like windows ME)...


later at highschool my skills and proficiency grew up even further and inspired by an amazing speech of Steve Wozniak in a campus party back in 2008, I finally decided this was my place, my safe place. not only I had all my life living surrounded by computers but also made the concient choise of choosing to become a nerd, not only I had chosen to become a systems engineer (equivalent in my country to computer science with a different focus) but I also radically rejected the traditional celebratory vacations of my graduation so I could pick my own college. (the one closest to my house for convenience) nothing fancy nothing expensive, it was private enough to have good laboratories and infrastructure, but not even well known to rank on the top 30 of my country, I took it as granted and began my 13 years of career... yep it took me that long to graduate.


due to several circumstances my mom decided to migrate to Germany without me, she provided enough support so I could study but I was living alongside my grandparents I had to take care of them, not only I had all my needs covered but I had to be available for them specially my grandfather whom was Oxygen dependant, he used to be a civil engineer as well and he even helped me out with my calculous homeworks but I couldt bring myself to pick a full semester and rush it up, I was later on suffering changes on classes and updates to Pensum I had to take extra semesters in my college, extra time wasted... early work experience as well...
those where my 20's.